'''Solomon Brandon Michael Clarke Thomas-Asante''' (born 29 December 1998) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a centre [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for {{English football updater|CoventrC}} club [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]. Born in England, he plays for the [[Ghana national football team|Ghana national team]].

Thomas-Asante began his career with [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]], where he made his professional debut aged in 2016 aged 17. After spells on loan with [[Sutton United F.C.|Sutton United]] and [[Oxford City F.C.|Oxford City]], he left Milton Keynes in 2019, spending a short spell at [[Ebbsfleet United F.C.|Ebbsfleet United]] before signing for [[Salford City F.C.|Salford City]]. While at Salford, he won his first trophy, the [[2019–20 EFL Trophy]].

== Club career ==

=== Milton Keynes Dons ===
Thomas-Asante joined [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]]' academy at the age of 12, progressing through various age groups and into the club's development squad. On 6 August 2016, following an impressive pre-season, he made his debut for the first team, featuring as a substitute in the 75th minute in a 1–0 away win to [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Shrewsbury Town 0–1 Milton Keynes Dons|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36930220|publisher=BBC Sport|access-date=25 September 2016|date=6 August 2016}}</ref> On 12 September, Thomas-Asante signed professional terms with the club, signing a one-year deal with an option of a further year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Thomas-Asante turns pro|url=http://www.mkdons.com/news/article/2016-17/thomas-asante-turns-pro-brandon-thomas-asante-mk-dons-brandon-thomas-asante-professional-mk-dons-academy-3304924.aspx |publisher=Milton Keynes Dons |access-date=13 September 2016|date=13 September 2016}}</ref> On 5 November, he scored his first professional goal for the club, scoring in a 3–2 home [[FA Cup]] first round win over [[Spennymoor Town F.C.|Spennymoor Town]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Report: MK Dons 3-2 Spennymoor Town|url=http://www.mkdons.com/news/article/2016-17/report-mk-dons-3-2-spennymoor-town-3400963.aspx|publisher=Milton Keynes Dons |date=5 November 2016|access-date=5 November 2016}}</ref> On 2 May 2017, following an impressive first season as a professional, Thomas-Asante was awarded the club's Academy Player of the Year for 2016–17.<ref name="Williams named Player of the Year">{{Cite web |url=http://www.mkdons.com/news/article/2016-17/williams-named-player-of-the-year-3702868.aspx |title=Williams named Player of the Year |publisher=Milton Keynes Dons |date=2 May 2017 |access-date=2 May 2017}}</ref> On 14 June, Thomas-Asante's contract was extended until summer 2018,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mkdons.com/news/2017/june/five-young-pros-to-remain-at-stadium-mk/ |title=Five young pros to remain at Stadium MK |publisher=Milton Keynes Dons |date=14 June 2017 |access-date=14 June 2017}}</ref> and on 26 January 2018 was extended a further year until the summer of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mkdons.com/news/2018/january/brandon-extends-dons-stay/ |title=Brandon extends Dons stay |publisher=Milton Keynes Dons |date=26 January 2018 |access-date=26 January 2018}}</ref>

====Loans, departure, spell with Ebbsfleet United====

After a brief loan spell with [[National League (division)|National League]] club [[Sutton United F.C.|Sutton United]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mkdons.com/news/2018/november/thomas-asante-joins-sutton-united-on-loan/ |title=Thomas-Asante joins Sutton United on loan |publisher=Milton Keynes Dons |date=23 November 2018 |access-date=24 November 2018}}</ref> Thomas-Asante joined [[National League South]] club [[Oxford City F.C.|Oxford City]] in late January 2019 until the end of the season, eventually going on to make 15 appearances and scoring three goals.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.oxfordcityfc.co.uk/news/thomas-asante-joins-on-loan-2390608.html |title=Thomas-Asante joins on Loan |publisher=Oxford City |date=28 January 2019 |access-date=28 January 2019 |archive-date=29 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129124310/http://www.oxfordcityfc.co.uk/news/thomas-asante-joins-on-loan-2390608.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> Following limited first team opportunities during the [[2018–19 Milton Keynes Dons F.C. season|2018–19 season]], Thomas-Asante confirmed on 11 May he would be leaving Milton Keynes following the expiry of his contract in June.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mkfm.com/news/mk-dons-news/brandon-thomas-asante-becomes-second-player-to-announce-mk-dons-departure-today/ |title=Brandon Thomas-Asante becomes second player to announce MK Dons departure today |publisher=MKFM.com |date=11 May 2019 |access-date=11 May 2019 }}</ref>

After a spell on trial with [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]], Thomas-Asante signed for [[National League (division)|National League]] club [[Ebbsfleet United F.C.|Ebbsfleet United]] on 9 August 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ebbsfleetunited.co.uk/brandon-lands-in-time-for-fylde-visit/ |title=Brandon lands in time for Fylde visit |publisher=Ebbsfleet United |date=9 August 2019 |access-date=9 August 2019 }}</ref>

===Salford City===
He then signed for [[Salford City F.C.|Salford City]] making his debut for the club on 3 September 2019 in a [[EFL Trophy]] match against Aston Villa Under 21's.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://salfordcityfc.co.uk/matches/salford-city-v-aston-villa-u21s-03091920/|title = Salford City 2–0 Aston Villa U21s &#124; Results 2019–20}}</ref> He made his league debut for the club as a substitute on 14 September.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49617862 |title=Salford City 0–2 Cheltenham Town |work=BBC Sport}}</ref> His first goal for the club came on [[Boxing Day]], scoring Salford's second in the 12th minute of a 3–1 victory against [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50847157 |title=Salford City 3–1 Crewe Alexandra |date=28 October 2020 |access-date=28 October 2020 |work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> He finished the 2019–20 campaign with six goals from 26 appearances in all competitions.

On 28 November 2020, Thomas-Asante received the first red-card of his career for a reckless foul on [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] goalkeeper [[Tom King (footballer, born 1995)|Tom King]], as Salford exited the FA Cup at the second round.<ref>{{cite web |last=Dunnett |first=Harry |url=http://www.salfordnow.co.uk/2020/11/28/match-report-salford-crash-out-of-fa-cup-after-asante-sees-red-finished/ |title=Salford crash out of FA Cup after Thomas-Asante sees red |work=Salford Now |date=28 November 2020 |access-date=2 September 2021}}</ref> He scored his first goal of the season against Leicester City U23s in the EFL Trophy group match that ended in a 3–3 draw after 90 minutes, eventually losing 9–8 on penalties in which he converted his penalty.<ref>{{Cite web |date=8 December 2020|title=Live Commentary - Salford City v Leicester City U-23|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/salford-city-vs-leicester-city-u21/439962 |access-date=15 December 2020|website=Sky Sports}}</ref> He played for Salford in the delayed [[2020 EFL Trophy final]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] against [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]].<ref name="2020EFLT"/> Thomas-Asante converted his penalty in the shootout as Salford won the final.<ref name="2020EFLT"/> On 19 March 2022, Thomas-Asante scored his first career [[hat-trick]] in a 5–1 home victory over [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60717372 |title=Salford City 5–1 Scunthorpe United |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=19 March 2022 |access-date=20 March 2022 }}</ref>

===West Bromwich Albion===
On 31 August 2022, Thomas-Asante signed for [[EFL Championship]] club [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] on a three-year contract for a fee reported to be in the region of £300,000, rejecting a move to [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/brandon-thomas-asante-west-brom-24895838 |title=Brandon Thomas-Asante to West Brom confirmed ahead of busy transfer deadline day |work=[[Birmingham Mail]] |publisher=[[Reach plc]] |date=31 August 2022 |access-date=31 August 2022 }}</ref> On 2 September 2022, Thomas-Asante made his debut and scored his first goal, a 98th-minute equaliser for West Brom in a 1–1 home draw against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62683201|title=West Brom 1–1 Burnley|work=BBC Sport|date=2 September 2022|access-date=11 May 2023}}</ref> Thomas-Asante finished his first West Brom season as the club's top goalscorer of the season with 9 goals, 7 of which in the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wba.co.uk/news/brandon-thomas-asante-wins-spreadex-top-goalscorer-award|title=Brandon Thomas-Asante wins Spreadex top goalscorer award|publisher=West Bromwich Albion|date=9 May 2023|access-date=11 May 2023}}</ref> His volley against [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] in November was voted as West Brom's 2022–23 goal of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wba.co.uk/news/brandon-thomas-asante-scoops-ideal-heating-goal-season-gong|title=Brandon Thomas-Asante scoops Ideal Heating goal of the season gong|publisher=West Bromwich Albion|date=5 May 2023|access-date=11 May 2023}}</ref>

===Coventry City===
On 1 August 2024, Thomas-Asante signed for Championship club [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] on a four-year contract for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web|title=Brandon Thomas-Asante signs for Coventry City|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cn05vpdexr7o|date=1 August 2024|access-date=1 August 2024}}</ref> On 3 August, he made his debut in a pre-season friendly against [[SV Werder Bremen]] who compete in the [[Bundesliga]]. On 27 August, Thomas-Asante scored his first goal for Coventry City in a 1–0 win against [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] in the second round of the [[2024–25 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]]. On 1 October, Thomas-Asante scored his first league goal for Coventry City in a 3–0 win against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]].

Thomas-Asante was named [[EFL Championship Player of the Month]] for October 2025 having scored six goals in as many matches as Coventry topped the league.<ref name="Oct25 POTM">{{cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/news/2025/november/14/sky-bet-championship--manager-and-player-of-the-month-october-winners/|title=Sky Bet Championship: Manager and Player of the Month October winners|website=www.efl.com|date=14 November 2025|accessdate=16 November 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
In December 2023, Thomas-Asante was pre-called up by the [[Ghana national football team]] for the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web |title=AFCON 2023 - PROVISIONAL SQUADS LIST|url=https://www.cafonline.com/media/szzh20fx/afcon-2023-provisional-squads-list.pdf|page=19}}</ref>

He made his debut for the [[Ghana national football team|Ghana national team]] on 10 June 2024 in a [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF Group G|World Cup qualifier]] against the [[Central African Republic national football team|Central African Republic]] at the [[Baba Yara Stadium]]. He substituted [[Mohammed Kudus]] in the 89th minute of a 4–3 Ghana victory.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=ESPN|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/687365/|title=Ghana v CAR game report|date=10 June 2024}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Ghana during a 2–1 defeat against Nigeria during the [[2025 Unity Cup]] on 28 May 2025.<ref>{{Cite news |date=28 May 2025 |title=Unity Cup: Dessers scores as S'Eagles beat Ghana 2-1 in London |url=https://www.punchng.com/unity-cup-dessers-scores-as-seagles-lead-ghana-2-0-at-halftime-in-london |access-date=29 May 2025 |newspaper=[[The Punch]]}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Born in England, Thomas-Asante is of Ghanaian and Jamaican descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sportsworldghana.com/ghanaian-striker-brandon-thomas-asante-scores-hat-trick-as-salford-city-wallop-scunthorpe-united/|title=Ghanaian striker Brandon Thomas-Asante scores hat-trick as Salford City wallop Scunthorpe United|date=19 March 2022}}</ref>

